(40, 11, 12, 50, 2, 12, 12, 'the violent take it by force', 'Violence and Working Out Salvation', 'This connection highlights the active engagement required in both passages. Matthew speaks of the ''violent'' taking the kingdom, while Philippians urges believers to ''work out'' their salvation, suggesting a similar intensity in spiritual pursuit.', 'theme', 0.524, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 12, 43, 6, 27, 27, NULL, 'Connection of Spiritual Labor', 'This connection highlights the contrast between earthly pursuits and spiritual endeavors. Both passages emphasize the importance of striving for what endures, with Matthew focusing on the forceful pursuit of the kingdom and John urging labor for everlasting life.', 'theme', 0.489, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 12, 40, 21, 23, 32, NULL, 'Authority and Response to John', 'Both passages emphasize the response to John the Baptist''s message. In Matthew 11:12, the violent take the kingdom by force, while in Matthew 21:32, the publicans and harlots believed John, contrasting with the chief priests'' rejection. This highlights the differing responses to the call of righteousness.', 'theme', 0.43299999999999994, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 13, 40, 5, 17, 18, NULL, 'Connection of Law and Prophets', 'This connection highlights the continuity between the law and the prophets, as both passages affirm their significance. Matthew 11:13 states that the law and prophets prophesied until John, while Matthew 5:17-18 emphasizes that Jesus came to fulfill them.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 13, 45, 3, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Law and Prophets', 'This connection highlights the continuity of the law and prophets in both passages. Matthew emphasizes that the prophets and the law prophesied until John, while Romans states that the righteousness of God is witnessed by the law and the prophets.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 13, 44, 13, 27, 27, NULL, 'Prophets and Their Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the role of the prophets in both passages. Matthew notes that the law and prophets prophesied until John, while Acts emphasizes that the rulers in Jerusalem did not recognize the voices of the prophets, thus fulfilling their messages in condemning Jesus.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 13, 39, 4, 6, 6, 'the prophets and the law prophesied', 'Prophetic Fulfillment and Restoration', 'This connection highlights the prophetic role of John as a bridge between the law and the coming restoration of relationships, as seen in Malachi. Both passages emphasize the importance of turning hearts to prevent divine judgment.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 13, 42, 24, 27, 27, 'the prophets', 'Connection of Prophets and Scriptures', 'This connection highlights the continuity of prophecy in the scriptures. Both passages emphasize the role of prophets in revealing God''s message, culminating in Jesus.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 13, 42, 24, 44, 44, NULL, 'Connection of Prophetic Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the role of the law and the prophets in relation to John and Jesus. Both passages emphasize that the law and the prophets are integral to understanding the fulfillment of God''s plan.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 13, 44, 3, 22, 24, 'the prophets and the law prophesied', 'Prophetic Continuity and Fulfillment', 'This connection highlights the continuity of prophecy, as both passages reference the role of prophets in God''s plan. Matthew 11:13 indicates that the law and prophets culminate with John, while Acts 3:22-24 emphasizes Moses'' prophecy of a coming prophet, linking the prophetic tradition to Jesus.', 'prophecy', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 14, 39, 4, 5, 5, 'this is Elias, which was for to come', 'Elijah''s Prophetic Role', 'This connection highlights the prophetic role of Elijah as mentioned in both passages. Matthew 11:14 identifies Jesus as the fulfillment of the prophecy in Malachi 4:5 regarding Elijah''s coming before the Lord''s day.', 'prophecy', 0.43999999999999995, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 14, 40, 17, 10, 13, 'this is Elias, which was for to come', 'Connection of Elias and John', 'Both passages emphasize the identity of Elias as John the Baptist. Matthew 11:14 states, ''this is Elias,'' while Matthew 17:13 clarifies that Jesus spoke of John the Baptist as Elias.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 14, 41, 9, 11, 13, 'this is Elias, which was for to come', 'Connection of Elijah''s Role', 'Both passages emphasize the role of Elias in relation to Jesus. Matthew identifies John the Baptist as Elias, while Mark confirms that Elias has indeed come, linking the two figures in their prophetic mission.', 'theme', 0.40499999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 14, 42, 1, 17, 17, 'this is Elias', 'Connection of Elias in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the role of Elias in preparing people for the Lord. Both passages emphasize the significance of Elias in turning hearts and making ready a people.', 'theme', 0.377, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 14, 43, 1, 21, 23, 'this is Elias, which was for to come', 'Connection of Elias and John', 'This connection highlights the identification of John the Baptist with Elijah, as suggested in Matthew 11:14. John denies being Elias but fulfills the role of a forerunner, echoing the prophetic call in Isaiah.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 14, 26, 2, 5, 5, 'this is Elias, which was for to come', 'Prophetic Recognition and Rebellion', 'This connection highlights the recognition of a prophet in both passages. Matthew speaks of Elias coming, while Ezekiel addresses a rebellious house that will know a prophet has been among them.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 14, 43, 16, 12, 12, NULL, 'Understanding Revelation and Reception', 'This connection highlights the theme of revelation and the readiness to receive it. In Matthew, the reference to Elias suggests a significant message that requires acceptance, while in John, the mention of things that cannot be borne indicates a limitation in understanding or readiness.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
