(40, 11, 15, 66, 2, 7, 7, 'He that hath ears to hear', 'Call to Listen and Overcome', 'This connection highlights the call to listen in both passages. Matthew emphasizes the importance of hearing, while Revelation extends this call to the churches, promising rewards for those who overcome.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 16, 42, 7, 31, 35, 'children sitting in the markets', 'Children in the Marketplace', 'Both passages emphasize the metaphor of children sitting in the marketplace, illustrating the generation''s refusal to respond to calls for joy or mourning. This connection highlights the contrasting reactions to John the Baptist and Jesus, who represent different approaches to God''s message.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 11, 16, 25, 2, 13, 13, NULL, 'Children and Comfort', 'Both passages emphasize the need for understanding and comfort in the face of distress. Matthew''s reference to children highlights a sense of innocence and simplicity, while Lamentations seeks to find a witness or comfort for the suffering of Jerusalem. This connection highlights the human desire for reassurance amidst turmoil.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
